Question: Which Harry Potter movie was among the American Film
Institute's 400 nominees for the top 100 American films of all time?
Hint: It wasn't 1, 2, or 4 (5 hadn't been released yet).

&quot;Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban,&quot; in addition to being the
best of the Potter films (notice that Alfonso Cuaron's vision of
Hogwarts, rather than Chris Columbus's, has defined the place in the
subsequent movies?), is a visually stunning work by any standard. In
fact, it's probably the most beautiful film of the last decade not
made by a director named Zhang. And the superb, evocative score is one
of the best of the decade as well, not to mention John Williams'
finest work in many years.

Here's hoping the Cuaron/Williams team returns to do justice to
&quot;Deathly Hallows.&quot;

Joe Ramirez
