*James* Newton Howard, actually. I agree that Williams sometimes
repeats himself, but probably no more so than any typical film
composer. And when he's inspired, he repeats himself much less than
the typical composer, because he has exceptional melodic gifts that
enable him to create distinctive motifs practically on demand. His
music for &quot;Azkaban&quot; was wonderful, and I think he would similarly rise
to the challenge of the Harry Potter finale. I'd hate to see (or
hear :)) Nicholas Hooper (&quot;Phoenix&quot;) or worse, Patrick Doyle
(&quot;Goblet&quot;) get the assignment again.

