I agree wholeheartedly with the second part of your statement, but
disagree with the first part. I would rephrase it as, &quot;POA wasn't 100%
faithful.&quot; On the whole, it is a very faithful adaptation of the
novel. Book fans nowadays seem to have extremely high standards for
fidelity in adaptations. There are still some people who gripe that
the 1995 BBC/A&amp;E miniseries version of &quot;Pride and Prejudice&quot; took a
few liberties, despite the fact that it devoted five hours of screen
time to a relatively short novel, preserved all sorts of subplots and
minor characters, and incorporated large amounts of original dialogue
into the screenplay. Truly unfaithful adaptations are things like the
happy-ending-obsessed Hollywood bastardizations of mid-century, or
title-only rewrites such as &quot;I Robot&quot; or the James Bond flicks. In
fact, all five of the Potter movies have been quite faithful by
historical studio standards, with the latter two somewhat less so
because of the greater length of the novels. This may be small
consolation to the fan whose favorite scene gets left out of the film,
but we should try to be objective.

